0. Data Preparation¶

Back to top

In HW2, we are instructed to obtain all the texts of different categories from this link (http://www.gutenberg.org/wiki/Children%27s_Instructional_Books_(Bookshelf).

In total, there are 104 texts with titles hyperlinked their corresponding urls to download from 10 categories (Misc., Graded Readers, Poetry Readers, Readers for English Speakers Learning Other Languages, Non-English Readers, About Readers, Science and Nature, History, Geography, Uncategorized).

The first step is to create BeautifulSoup object with base url and html.parser for getting urls and ebook titles, and obtain the plain text UTF-8 url links for all the category books with wget function. In this step, the pattern shared in hyperlinks help convert to the final following format example: http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/11313/pg11313.txt.

The second step is to clean the data by removing the tagged Gutenberg license and other unrelated information. This step will help analyze text data more accurately on lexical diversity, long-word vocabulary size, and text difficult score.

## remove the tagged gutenberg license information
def remove_gutenberg_license(text_raw) :
    
    head1 = '*** START OF THIS PROJECT GUTENBERG EBOOK'
    head2 = '*** START OF THE PROJECT GUTENBERG EBOOK'
    head3 = '***START OF THE PROJECT GUTENBERG EBOOK'
    
    tail1 = 'End of the Project Gutenberg EBook'
    tail2 = 'End of Project Gutenberg'
    tail3 = '***END OF THE PROJECT GUTENBERG EBOOK'
    
    try :
        book_tail_text = text_raw.split(head1, 1)[1]
    
    except IndexError:
        try :
            book_tail_text = text_raw.split(head2, 1)[1]
            
        except IndexError:
            book_tail_text = text_raw.split(head3, 1)[1]
    
    text_without_license = book_tail_text.split(tail1, 1)[0]
    
    if(len(text_without_license) == len(book_tail_text)) :
        text_without_license = book_tail_text.split(tail2, 1)[0]
    
    if(len(text_without_license) == len(book_tail_text)) :
        text_without_license = book_tail_text.split(tail3, 1)[0]

    return text_without_license

## lexical diversity score as given in nltk site
def lexical_diversity(my_text_data): 
    tokens = len(my_text_data)
    types = len(set(my_text_data)) 
    diversity_score = types / tokens 
    return diversity_score
In [17]:
## remove all non-alpha characters
def clean_text(start_text) :
    text = [re.sub('^((?![a-zA-Z ]).)*$', '', x) for x in start_text]
    text = [re.sub('_', '', x) for x in text]
    text = [x.lower() for x in text]
    text = [x for x in text if x != '']
    return text

    num_words = len(readers.words(fileid))
    tokens = len(readers.words(fileid))
    types = len(set(readers.words(fileid)))
    
    num_vocab = len(set(w.lower() for w in readers.words(fileid)))

    ldiv = lexical_diversity(rtxt)

    table_data = {'text_name' : fileid,'num_chars' : num_chars,'num_words' : num_words, 'num_vocab' : num_vocab,

    df_tbl = pd.DataFrame(table_data,

1.4 - Explain in a short paragraph¶

Back to top

In order to create a method for scoring the vocabulary size of text, the maximum vocabulary size 14,611 unique words in "McGuffeys Sixth Eclectic Reader" was set to 1 and used to normalize other individual text scores. The lexical diversity score was calculated as previously in HW1 by the ratio of type to token for each of the 104 texts after some basic cleanings and converting to low case letters.

For normalizing the score from 0 to 1, the vocabulary size normalization score for each text was calculated as the simple ratio of the vocabulary size of each text to the largest vocabulary size of any text. The score distributions for each text are shown the barplots in section 1.3. Most books categories have vocab_normalized scores between 0.2 and 0.8. "McGuffeys Sixth Eclectic Reader" is the highest at 1, and "Little Present by Unknown" is the lowest at 0.06.

## fine-grained selection of words (page 19: Bird-Klein w > 15)
def long_words(text_input) :    
    text_unique = set(text_input)    
    long_words = [w for w in text_unique if len(w) > 10] # use 10 here
    longest = sorted(long_words, key = len, reverse = True)[0]
    return longest
In [28]:
## remove all non-alpha characters
def clean_text(start_text) :
    text = [re.sub('^((?![a-zA-Z ]).)*$', '', x) for x in start_text]
    text = [x.lower() for x in text]
    text = [x for x in text if x != '']
    return text

## sample regex breakdones
# .  for matching any single character 
# ^  for matching the start of the string  
# $  for matching the end of the string 
# *  for matching zero or more cases of the previous mentioned regex before the  *  symbol in the pattern 
# ?  for matching zero or one case of the previous mentioned regex before the  ?  symbol in the pattern  
# \w  for matching alphanumeric characters also depicted as [a-zA-Z0-9_]

2.4 - Explain in a short paragraph¶

Back to top

In order to create a method for scoring the long-word vocabulary size of text, the longest word identified among all of the texts screened is "osieontarioreadersfourth00miniuoft" in "A Modern History, From the Time of Luther ..." with 34 characters. After further checking, this word is portion of hyperlink name. The following longest words such as "gehoorzaamheidsinstinct", "_m_a_j_e_st_i_c_a_ll_y", and "kristenbernikovstrade" are from other languages, but not the English words. Therefore, the long-word vocabulary is only a relatively accurate method for normalizing all words, and normalize the word vocabulary with 34 as reference.

For normalizing the score from 0 to 1, the vocabulary length normalization score for each text was calculated as the simple ratio of the vocabulary length of each text to the maximum vocabulary length (34). The score distributions for each text are shown the barplots in section 2.3.

3.3 Explain when this score is applied to same graded texts used in HW1¶

Back to top

The text difficulty score (TDS) used in this homework was calculated with the equal weight of normalized values of lexical diversity score, vocabulary size score, and vocabulary length score. In other words, we took the average of these three score to make TDS for applying to same graded texts used in homework 1.

The TDS score meets expectation better than using single scoring methods as discussed previously. The normalized vocabulary size in text ('vocab_nrml') and the normalized vocabulary length in text ('word_length_nrml) indicate the expected text difficulties with varied levels in the same decreasing rends from the 6th to the 2nd grader McGuffey's textbooks. Different trends of these two scores was observed with the lexical diversity score which was calculated as the ratio of type to token for each of the 104 texts after some basic cleanings and converting to low case letters.

As shown in the barplots, TDS score method is relatively more accurate to reflect the text difficulties for McGuffey readers after adjusting these three scoring methods with equal weights.

There are still rooms to improve TDS scoring method, such as to choose different weights, further clean the texts, consider different languages.
